in slogging&apos;s official #programming channel and has been edited for readability. Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 9:40 PM Businesses have Messy Emails [pt 2] Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 9:41 PM Jumping to sales teams. Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:14 PM Security, sensitive information sharing, automation, tracking, and managing sales pipelines and business contacts. Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:22 PM How often do you reading your emails from your personal devices? Do you forward some sensitive information between your work address and personal email address? Let&apos;s talk about security. Links, Links, Links Monitor for Phishing and Scam Attempts. Ensure that you are cautious in the emails that you open, especially from unfamiliar sources. In the event of a phishing attempt, make sure to report it directly to your IT department and ensure that they have the most time possible to prevent any potential data breaches. While I&apos;m not sure if it&apos;s doable in our modern world, but It’s important to make sure that all your client information is kept in one place, especially when working remotely. This is not only to reduce general data loss and increase efficiency but also to reduce the risk of data theft. The more places or applications you use to store your data, statistically, the greater chance that one of them will suffer a data breach. A lot of stuff we are doing with our mobile phones nowadays While working remotely, companies have less control over the networks that employees use. In a physical office environment, everyone uses the same network that the business has provided, meaning it’s safe and secure for all. While working from different locations, sales teams have more opportunities to connect to unsecured networks, which is one of the most common ways for data to be leaked or stolen. VPNs! Identity and Access Management solutions! Having a Universal Method of Communication! Haha, looks like it&apos;s impossible for small companies! singular form or method of communication can solve many problems companies face, especially when it comes to data security. Once again, spreading yourself too thin over several different sites and ways of communication can open yourself up to cyberattacks. In addition to having more security issues related to the different platforms, it also becomes easier for hackers to perform phishing attempts or gain access to private information and data due to potential confusion. When you have a lot of employees all communicating across multiple platforms with different uses, confusion is bound to happen. According to , over 1/5th of cybersecurity breaches occur due to human error, which goes to show, that streamlining communication as much as possible can reduce crucial errors. https://enterprise.verizon.com/resources/reports/2019-data-breach-investigations-report.pdf Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:34 PM Guys from Nord are providing cool service. Zero Trust security solutions Secure identities Ensure authorized personnel is accessing your user accounts, and nobody else. Secure devices. with alerts to admins Secure access to applications aka if your team is located in the US, nobody from Europe must be able to log in. or better have a whitelist of IPs.(yeah, no to working from a coffee, sorry not sorry) Secure data Secure network access &gt; long passwords, encryption, backups and often review it again and again Visibility, automation, etc. Activity monitoring and logging So many things to talk about! Like how to prevent human errors? I don&apos;t have a proper answer. While planning and automation can help. And expertise. Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:37 PM Having a team of salespeople? The higher the number, the more risks and higher the probability of problems Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:37 PM Cross-teams collaboration can also be an issue Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:38 PM Salespeople have access to lots of data... in my previous article, I told a few stories, but I&apos;m sure, there are more. Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:40 PM and it&apos;s hard to manage everything and prevent from leaking some personal information like bank details, personal email addresses, or just making a typo in email address and sending things to a wrong person Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:41 PM Cool article: https://www.tessian.com/research/the-psychology-of-human-error/ Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:42 PM While big companies have probably a great software and processes inside - there are a lot of things to do for a small companies Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:43 PM Yeah, it&apos;s hard to balance all risks at the same time, especially if your company is growing quickly and you have a lot of chats on Slack https://www.tessian.com/research/the-state-of-data-loss-prevention-2020/ Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:45 PM Threats prevention, Education, Automation, Great infrastructure setup, and centralized data storage might help Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:46 PM Training, Training, Training! Train your teammates. Reading list: Arthur Tkachenko Jun 2, 2022, 10:48 PM https://mapmycustomers.me/blog/data-security-awareness-and-its-importance-for-sales-reps/ https://intaso.co/news/building-a-high-performing-cyber-security-sales-team/ https://www.rossross.com/blog/top-5-cyber-security-tips-for-sales-teams https://www.stillpointsystems.com/your-sales-marketing-staffs-role-in-cyber-security/ https://www.nasp.com/blog/why-cybersecurity-is-now-a-more-important-topic-than-ever-for-remote-sales-teams/ https://securityboulevard.com/2020/01/the-importance-of-training-your-sales-team-avast/ Part one of this series: . https://hackernoon.com/businesses-have-messy-emails"}</script><link rel="preload" as="image" imagesrcset="/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.hackernoon.com%2Fimages%2F3nhao37bBEfHA9RTQ0WNVWfXPD02-8i93qfc.jpeg&amp;w=640&amp;q=75 1x, /_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.hackernoon.com%2Fimages%2F3nhao37bBEfHA9RTQ0WNVWfXPD02-8i93qfc.jpeg&am